column1: Will the UAE’s Customer Happiness Index be higher for 2020 as compared to 2019?

column6: The UAE use a survey to produce a composite indicator to measure the resident’s satisfaction of their living standards, that include experiences with Government Departments and perspectives on income level, life expectancy, anti-corruption and freedom to make personal choices. Emiratis make up 20% of the population which means most residents choose to live and work there. There is no income tax, homelessness and a safe environment with very low crime rate. The Governments Happiness Agenda comprises of the following criteria that are Discover (needs); Change (policies); Educate (create awareness); Measure. For example, the 2019 survey had the following:-
The trend is quite static, covid may push down.
-Invading the space -Start using solar energy -Success in COVID 19

Couldn't find any details about this particular survey, but here is more info about the UAE's general promotion of happiness and wellbeing. [1][2] While there is a lot of uncertainty surrounding this question, the UAE is clearly spending a lot of time and energy on these programs. Some commenters have floated COVID-19 as a reason against thinking the index will be higher, and this may have some validity as Dubai's change in subjective well-being decreased by 0.263 points in 2020. [3, page 56] However, the report also predicts that Dubai will be 21st in well-being, up from their current spot in 39th. [3, appendix] I personally think that the efforts of the government will show up in next year's index, but there are too many unknowns to assign a high probability.

The more I look at this, the more I regret forecasting it. This is a rather subjective and obscure question, and I think @sebawi has the most salient and cogent assessment of the situation of all: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1046503
Still feels likely, but scaling back to respond to the consensus.
Sorry Prince, happiness level will inevitably decline in 2020, but its always good to set your goals high.

There are a set of issues that complicate the forecast due to a lack of information on how the index is constructed (- at least I couldn't find it, if you have found more information, please comment).
It depends on how many tourists vote for a good service as well as the UAE inhabitants are satisfied with the service in their country.
What will the level of PPE worn by flight crew do to customer satisfaction?
UAE has hit the happiest country within the region for six years in a row.

2020 will be a positive year for the UAE. A ruler with a strong track record and devout following. With one of the highest per-capita testing rates in the world, the UAE is leading global efforts to contain the spread of COVID-19. This favorable response combined with financially incentivizing high levels of customer service supports the likelihood of a higher Customer Happiness level in 2020.

Knee-jerk prediction, will investigate further: Rationale being... C19 may sour many moods. 85.2% is already a high bar to beat; that said, I'm sure it is possible. Throw enough money at something and yeah, 99.9% is possible or at least, anything can *appear* to be achived.
